The villa is often mistaken for a wandering star, that appears to burn brighter than all the rest in the night sky. To get to the villa, you must take a shuttle that can only be reserved in the Elite level Sky Beds, located in the Upper-Five districts. None of the shuttles from the lower district can gain access, though some have tried. From the deepest trenches of the city, in the canals and the flooded streets--some say they can spot the villa as it passes over their district, while others have only ever seen its reflection in the black water. After its construction, those below looked to it as a grand beacon of hope, the promise of relief from the floods. But if you’ve ever been inside and seen what happens after the sun sets, you would know it’s all a lie. Another false hope. Those who’ve spent the extortionate sum to reach it can see how it flashes with many colored lights and pulses to the sound of music. An entire landmass of property rotating gently in place with streamlined curves and overhanging rooftops that seem to move in the direction of the wind. Inside is a palace of opulent splendor, endless partying and reckless indulgences. A place where polar ice sculptures hiss and crackle with flowing champagne and reclaimed-wine is served from diamond decanters. Some have called it the Floating Five Acres, some call it the Palace in the Clouds, the Olympus Peak, the Night Sun, the Sky Villa. I call it home.

The shallow depth of field focuses on the faces of the black cowboy man and woman, highlighting their expressions and emphasizing the theme of the photo. The lighting is expertly done, with a balance of natural and artificial light that creates a stunning contrast between the hot, blazing firework displays and the cool and calm demeanor of the cowboys. The atmosphere is electric, with a sense of freedom, excitement and pure thrill. The details of the photo are hyper-realistic and truly captivating, with every piece of clothing, every hair on the horses' manes and every piece of equipment expertly captured. This image is truly a masterpiece of photography.
